Support for democracy in Latin America continues to grow, like private enterprise.
Crime has become a greater concern than unemployment.
And Brazil is seen as more influential than the United States in much of the region.
These are some of the conclusions of the last poll taken Latinobarómetro in 18 countries and published exclusively by The Economist.
Since the survey was conducted on a regular basis since 1995, it tracks changes in attitudes in the region.
Two related elements emerge from the results of this year's survey, conducted in September and early October.
The first is fairly sunny mood of Latin America.
The second is the increasing stability of attitudes toward democracy and its key institutions.
Support for democracy has increased substantially in several countries on the Pacific rim of South America (see Table 1).
For example in Peru, where economic growth has averaged 6% per year since 2002, support for democracy rose from a minimum of 40% in 2005 to 61% this year.
It has also increased in Mexico, where the economy has recovered after a sharp drop in production last year.
But only about half of respondents in Mexico and Brazil, the two most populous countries in the region are convinced democrats, thus lowering the regional average (see Table 2).
Some 44% of respondents in the region have expressed satisfaction with how democracy in their country working in practice and is the same number as last year but with a sharp increase on the 25% in 2001 (Chart 3)
Some 34% said they had confidence in their parliament and 45% in their government, the same as last year in both cases, but up sharply compared to 2003 (respectively 17% and 24%).
Ten years ago, the economic problems in Latin America have undermined support for democracy.
If this held good during the global financial crisis is certainly due to the fact that many American countries have experienced a brief recession and have enjoyed a strong recovery.
In addition, a network of social security has helped protect the poor.
(The UN Economic Commission for Latin America reported this week that the number of Latin Americans living in poverty rose only slightly in 2009 and fell again this year to 32%.)
But the mood varies considerably from one country to another (see Chart 4).
The economic performance of Brazil and the popularity of its outgoing president, Luiz Inacio Lula da Silva, resulting in a widespread perception of progress
What is more rare in Mexico and Central America where the recession was more severe and where violent crimes have increased.
This is only the second time since the survey began more than respondents across the whole of Latin America have cited the crime rather than unemployment as the biggest problem for their country (see Table 5).
About 31% say they or their loved one have suffered a crime during the past year, however, this figure is down from 38% last year and is the most lowest since 1995.
A more robust economic performance is reflected in the increased support for private enterprise and market economy: about 71% of respondents in the region say that private enterprise is essential for development, against 56% in 2007 (cf. Chart 6).
Some 58% believe that the market economy is the only system that will make their developed country, against 47% last year.
Interestingly, 62% of respondents in Venezuela this view (and 80% support private enterprise), even if their leftist president, Hugo Chavez expropriated many private companies.
Brazil is the greatest leader in the region, mentioned by 19% of respondents (against 18% last year), followed by USA (9%, unchanged from last year) and Venezuela (9%, down 11% since last year)
But the United States are considered the most influential country by respondents in Mexico and much of Central America, while Venezuela has the distinction of Ecuador, the Dominican Republic and Nicaragua.
