Climate: how France hack its funding commitment
A year after the Copenhagen, it is time to evaluate compliance with promises of funding released quickly (so-called fast start and early funding) made by developed countries.
And large French hacks are revealed.
In the Copenhagen agreement, developed countries pledged to provide $ 30 billion between 2010 and 2012.
The European Union has pledged 7.2 billion euros over three years and France 1.26 billion euros (420 million per year).
At the opening of the COP16, the EU has released all the stops to persuade its partners in the reality of its commitment to fast-start funding: report detailing the activities of its member states, press conference, large side event , distribution of leaflets ...
Operation Transparency is valuable and valued at fair value: developing countries and civil society would like all developed countries do the same with the same level of accuracy.
The EU announced that in 2010 reached 2.2 billion euros, which puts it on track for meeting its commitment of $ 7.2 billion in 2012.
But when we look in detail, things are more complicated.
This money should be, according to the Copenhagen agreement, "new and additional" to ensure that an extra effort be made without the expense of ODA.
Unfortunately, there is no agreement on what "new and additional."
While the European Commission had proposed a harmonization, some member states including France, have blocked the process.
Today, everyone chooses the model that suits him best.
The European Commission has for example considered as the reference year 2009: international funding are maintained, and it adds 150 million over three years for financing fast start.
Other countries have chosen similar references in terms of year or in terms of level of official development assistance.
In contrast, France considers that funding for "all new projects" of 2010 are "new and additional."
In other words, there is no reference to previous years' expenditures or overall level of ODA.
Specifically, the total support of France for developing countries may remain stable (or even decrease), it claims to respect its commitment to finance "new and additional" ...
Another crucial element, the distribution of grants and loans.
Again, there are no rules and each chooses its mode of calculation.
Some, like France, consider that 1 equals 1 lent € € given.
Obviously, it is difficult to justify: the effort is not comparable.
If the use of loans may be justified for certain investments that are profitable (often projects related to the mitigation of emissions based on more efficient technologies), it is misleading to present one euro we will recover as equivalent a euro that is given ... At most, should be counted as part of its commitment that the cost of the loan to the lending country (the equivalent of an interest rate).
But France has no need of such reasoning: it "respects" its commitment of 420 million euros by 91.5% of loans (389.8 million euros) and 8.5% of gifts (36.1 million) - see EU document to check for yourself.
It is the only EU country to use the loan so massively.
Germany requires it to 46%, while Denmark, the Netherlands and Slovakia (by others) are meeting their commitments with 100% grants.
In other words, when the vast majority of the European Union puts 1 € to meet its commitment, France takes only 10 cents and considers that the effort is comparable.
Pretty hocus-pocus!
In summary, in its funding fast start, France operates a double fraud: one on the evolution of the action in time and secondly on the reality of the financial effort.
Spending only 36.1 million euros, it happens to believe that she spends 420 million "new and additional" in line with its promises.
The manipulation of the Ministry of Finance (since it seems that it has made Bercy arbitration) could have a double negative impact, both within the EU (why the other member states continue to give s' just lend?) and in negotiations since developing countries are not completely fooled ...
The chapter on early funding is a small matter of relative short term, relative to all discussions on climate.
But it might be a grain of sand over the huge machine called the UNFCCC.
Hopefully it will not be the case.
Anyway, it is essential to draw lessons from this first year of funding early.
First, France could announce a change in its accounting method for the years 2011 and 2012, in a spirit of respect and equity commitments with other countries of the European Union.
But above all, France could advance discussions on issues of long-term financing (other crucial chapter discussed now): we will not escape the question of "additionality" or method of accounting for loans.
France could change its position to become as progressive on these issues it is on others.
The hope is therefore based on the new Environment Minister, Mrs Kosciusko-Morizet, who will arrive in Cancun next week.
A surprise announcement on the fast start of France and its vision of "additionality" and the use of loans would likely increase the level of international confidence necessary to move forward in discussions.
